<br>
But regardless, the only country Seattle is close to is Canada, and since Canadians speak English as one of their official languages, I dont' think you guys are going to have a lot of trouble interpreting.<br>
<br>
Here in Texas, however, it's an entirely different ball game. Due to the ease of slipping through the border, and the vast amounts of hispanics in Texas, everything is written (nearly) as bi-lingual. Our entire culture is divided between the rampant clash between the two countries.<br>
<br>
They are teaching children Spanish in school, but for what purpose? In the United States, English is the official language, and most natives don't even speak it as well as I feel they should, so why are we wasting education time on teaching them a language that isn't even native to their country.<br>
<br>
Everyday at work, I am around several groups of people who speak little or no English. We are a UNITED nation, why should we promote this gap between cultures. I don't want to disclose an entire race based upon their culture, that's fine and dandy. I do, however, want them to be able to speak the language of the country I choose to live in.<br>
<br>
If I ever moved to another country, you can bet I would do my best to learn their language, out of courtesy both for the people of the nation, as well as for the nation itself. If the nation is so wonderful that I would want to live their above anywhere else, the least I can do is learn the official language set precedent.<br>
<br>
It is a drain on the tax dollars we put forth everyday, to interpret and provide this continuing rift between languages. It is absolutely true that we were a country founded upon immigration, and people from all nationalities and creeds. But that was ~250 years ago. I guarantee you the descendants of those fabled settling pioneers all speak English now. <br>
<br>
Times change, we are no longer a country built upon immigration, and to provide any means that prevents the bonding of us &quot;one nation, undivided&quot; is deragatory to everything we can accomplish.<br>
<br>
In my teen years, I was turned down a job at a fast food place because I wasn't bi-lingual. That's right, never mind my ability to dictate my feelings and my prowess in the english language, much less my work ethic and abilities, I didn't speak a language FOREIGN to my country, so I wasn't qualified.<br>
<br>
Languages are a beautiful thing, and help in preserving and expressing the beauty and differences each culture has to offer. I've picked up lots of spanish, french, and german both from a fascination standpoint, and an ability standpoint. But as an American citizen, whether legally or not, it is our duty to speak and write the language set forward by our government, and everytime you ignore or promote any argument to allow a language barrier to exist, you promote all of the negatives with a culture gap. Racism, nationalism, distrust, and miscommunication.<br>
<br>
Think about it.<br>
<br>
