<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> <br>
Of course you don't see a parallel gap between races, you live in Seattle.<br>
<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Like I said, I *am* the gap, being an American raised immigrant who'll never be fully accepted by Americans nor the Chinese.  Guess that's why I got thrown in therapy when I was a teen /boggle.<br>
<br>
Until each and every one of you has gone to try to make a living for yourself in a foreign country, you will never know where I'm coming from.  I'm not Aryan enough for the Americans just on the basis of what I eat and how I look, yet I'm always going to be too Americanized for those back in my homeland.  For most immigrants, we have no homeland.  I have absolutely no inkling of patriotism in me.  I get treated like I'm a second rate human being by Americans (Political Correctness ring a bell?) and by those who share my ethnic heritage (proud, pompous, selfish American brats is what we get called).  Most of you who know me know that I'm not politically minded.  I could give two sh!ts about the feminist revolution or equal opportunity.  Why?  Because it's those very fights and causes that have made my life uneasy.  Glory to the cause.  Well, you know what?  Fvck the cause because if you look at all your comments, the cause has lost.<br>
<br>
Trust me people, it's still a white man's world.  Your precious Anglicized bubble hasn't been burst.  My house was subject to arson in 1989 in a suburb in Los Angeles because we were the wrong skin color.  My family has suffered rape by white employers, and I lost my childhood when my mother spent 10 years of her life fighting appeal after appeal because the American courts accepted the bribes from the mighty white corporation to cover up the incidents.  So, stfu and rest happy because it's still your world out there.  It never stopped being your world.  I would know, because I'm still knocking on the door asking to be let in.<br>
<br>
Learn some @#%$ appreciation, for Christ's sake.  You all live in the best frikkin country in the world and you still have something to complain about?  Get off your azzes and travel and get a good look at how things are elsewhere.<br>
<br>
I see a whole lot of you whining about a whole lot of nothing.  Have a problem with legal documents written in Spanish?  Well, fvck, a lot of you Americans born and raised on U.S. soil can't even read a legal document without the help of a paralegal or attorney.  It's called legal 'jargon' for a reason.  So until each and every American can read legal documents a-okay all by themselves and completely comprehend them without outside help, I don't see why a copy written in Spanish, Chinese, Vietnamese, French, etc., is such a problem.  There's a word called hypocrisy I think a lot of you should look up.  My family speaks English perfectly fine but when we're going to pen our signature down on something legally binding, I'd sure as hell like for them to read it in a language they fully comprehend.  Just because someone wants a copy of a document in another language is no fvcking indication they can't speak conversational English.<br>
<br>
Sorry for the negativity, Nekiah, trust me it wasn't directed at you.<br>
<br>
So, basically, stfu because it's still your own @#%$ country.  Martin Luther King, Jr. and the other great activists may have made a dent, but look over your posts carefully and you'll see just as I have that many of his teachings have been lost.  <br>
<br>
Nobody is owed anything.  Immigrants don't owe anything to you and you don't owe anything to them.  Want the cultural gap to lessen?  How about you start changing your attitude about foreigners, first?  Instead of wondering how you should treat them, just go ahead and treat them like a normal human being.<br>
<br>
I think a lot of you lose sight that we are humans.  We're not aliens.  If you all can't pick up a language easily then it's tough for us, as well.  You can't stand criticism well?  Newsflash, not many people can, and your cold, unfeeling criticism based on superficial flaws is demeaning and spiteful.  I can't explain to you how much it hurts me as a person when I see people like you go off about rants like this.  It hurts me because it reassures me mainstream America still thinks I don't belong here, even though I've lived all but one year of my life in America.  All these comments do is assure me that the same a$$holes who tried to wreck my family's life (/wave Prudential Insurance, Co.) are still alive in mainstream America.  Their spirit lives on in every angry, bigotted, racist rant.<br>
<br>
Welcome to the land of the free, now, if you'll step off the boat, there's a hot cowbrand waiting for you to mark you as a second rate citizen and someone who doesn't belong here.  I have mine on my arm, want to see it?  Everytime you guys go off about an inane topic like this, I get another one, and so does every other immigrant who's worked hard to make a living here, only to find citizenship is a far cry from acceptance.<br>
<br>
Think this isn't what you're doing now?  Look again.  *We* make you miserable because we don't speak your language to the degree of fluency *you* prefer.  *We* have been like mice infiltrating your white suburbs, and that makes *you* uncomfortable.<br>
<br>
I'm sorry I wasn't born the right skin color or in the right country and I'm sorry my people don't speak enough English to make you all feel comfortable living your happy little carefree no-worries-no-poverty-there-is-always-welfare lives.  Hell, I'm sorry I was even born, because the truth is, many people just like you have made me wish I wasn't born at all throughout my life, because the pain felt from being hated or demeaned purely based on skin color and ethnicity hurts a person to their core.  The entire soul cries when you demean a person on superficial values.  Language, in the end, is just a means of communication.  I speak English.  What does that really tell you about a person?  Nothing.<br>
<br>
When you all feel like finally treating people like human beings no different than yourselves, only then will the cultural gap lessen.  It's only through patience, compassion, and understanding that this goal will be accomplished.  But until *you* are willing to let go of the hate, the prejudice (thinking immigrants don't speak a lick of English just because they'd like a copy of a legal document in another language is pretty damn shallow), and the overall selfish behavior (that you're owed something by others, such as comfort from hearing only English), this isn't going anywhere.<br>
<br>
So, yes, it's true.  America does cause a lot of its own problems.  When we all look in the mirror, we see the problem staring back at us.  The problem is, we don't acknowledge the problem, and well, the Devil's won. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#575757><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ulaoke.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Laoke</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Veteran</span><br>  Posts: 1334<br> <font color=#E9D756>(9/3/02 4:31:17 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub4.ezboard.com/femarrdragonsandplanes.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=3596.topic&index=25>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Silly Aishen</span><hr size=1> /applaud Aishen<br>
