Unfortunately, that has nothing at all to do with what I was talking about, nor the original poster. If you'll refer to my post, you'll notice my main (and mostly only) gripe was in regards to people who <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> cannot</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> speak English.<br>
<br>
I think racism is an idiotic venture. People have more than enough stupidity on their own to lump them based upon stereotypes. But regardless of the evils of racism, that doesn't change the fact that <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b>  You're in America! Speak English! </b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> <br>
<br>
About the paralegal argument, that's a very good point, and I think that for legal documents, any and every step should be taken to provide as much clarity to anything. Legal documents are confusing, and are a separate situation.<br>
<br>
I have more of an inkling to the situation where bi-lingual signs are posted everywhere, directions for use are tri-lingual, and all of the other little un-neccesary steps taken that allow people to not speak English.<br>
<br>
I'm not an evil emporer, I don't expect any particular race to predominate America, all I want is a unified country where everyone speaks the same language.<br>
<br>
Nekiah Dragonsbane<br>
