<br>
I agree, Gloriana, that phonetics are at their most prime learning stage during the 4-10 year period. You're right on the money. But the lackadaisical methods of public school systems <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> prevent</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> bi-lingual teaching institutions to be effective, and ultimately fail; whereas promoting English in that same time frame <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><i> would</i><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> be effective, and here's why.<br>
<br>
Due to the language barriers and vast differences between the romance languages and English, children (and adults) need a constant stream of use in order to retain knowledge. I constantly hear of people talking about how they've lost a large majority of the alternate language they took in high school and/or college.<br>
<br>
The reason is because they don't practice. And we can't expect children in a gradeschool situation to become fluent and practice that fluency on a regular basis, when the majority of their culture doesn't speak that same language. Sure there's the spanish channel on T.V., but by the complex equation of &quot;effort/laziness&quot; we see that there's a difference between idealism, and practicality.<br>
<br>
And this of course is assuming the child achieves fluency, based off of 5 hours a week in class being mass taught spanish. What's going to happen is kids learn how to count, tell the time, and basic noun usage.<br>
<br>
How useful is that? Honestly? Since school hours are so precious anyway, and children are burdened with homework everyday since the school day isn't long enough, why would anyone support a program that promotes inefficiency?<br>
<br>
If you took this 5 hours a week and instead of branching your time into multiple languages spent a concentrated effort on the English language, you'd achieve much more beneficial results.<br>
<br>
The English language <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> will</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END--> be constantly streamed throughout the childs life. By spending time not on noun usage, and instead focusing on grammar usage, improved spelling and vocabulary, you would notice results that actually effect childrens lives. <br>
<br>
And don't get me started on children that are poor at English, that are required to take Spanish. Children who are behind their class in reading skills are wasting time falling behind in another language, instead of being able to spend the time developing these underused skills.<br>
<br>
One of the number one skills employers look for is communication skills, both written and oral. Everyone likes speaking to someone who is well spoken, and by allowing more time on our native tongue, we would achieve and improve upon that. <br>
<br>
There is no need in generalizing our efforts, when we would achieve much more spectacular results by focusing our energies into one effect, rather than several. All we are achieving now is a waste of already precious school budget and time, which doesn't benefit anyone.<br>
<br>
Nekiah Dragonsbane<br>
