<br>
i live in canada and there are two official languages here... well obviously, we have a problem with some quebecois whom wants to seperate quebec from canada... well, this is directly related to the concept and the idea of nationalism.<br>
<br>
what makes a nation-state?<br>
remember, before the end of 18th century, and the the unity of italy and germany, there is no such thing as nationalism.  the so called &quot;borders&quot; are not well defined, they were more like zones of control - cities are surrounded by huge walls, and the people don't really care about where that ideally invisible-thin-line-that-has-no-thickness (aka border) lies either.  without nationalism, the united states wouldn't bother to get united in the first place - without the concept of a nation-state, the uniting states would be nothing, state(s) in and of itself doesn't make a nation.<br>
<br>
a formation of a nation is not a simple phenomenon, i'll say.<br>
<br>
here's some quote from john breuilly (who wrote nationalism and the state):<br>
<br>
&quot;The term 'nationalism' is used to refer to political movements seeking or exercising state power and justifying such actions with nationalist arguments. <br>
<br>
&quot;A nationalist argument is a political doctrine built upon three basic assertions:<br>
<br>
a) There exists a nation with an explicit and peculiar character. <br>
b) The interests and values of this nation take priority over all other interests and values. <br>
c) The nation must be as independent as possible. This usually requires at least the attainment of political sovereignity.&quot;<br>
<br>
language can be, and is often, considered as an explicit and peculiar character of a nation.  francophones are different from anglophones, simple as that, and as simple as canada tried to included both french and english into the catagory of the official languages (from very early on, mind you), there are still many separaists remain in quebec.  what does this say about language and nation?  well, i'm not saying quebec should stay or not, and neither am i saying the united states should have english as the official language, but your land of the free is a nation with a definite border, a definite form of citizenship, a system of government, and its national interest...<br>
<br>
a common language and the loyality to the nation was the basic requirement in the early french republic (obviously after the revolution), and i'm quite sure the american republic (it is not a democracy!  if you still need to doubt, wait until you read all about the ills of the real democracy in ancient athens and you'll be glad that you are not in a real democracy) has more or less the same ideal, which was different from the germanic empire ideal of a single race.<br>
<br>
some ppl here seems to see the nagative side of nationalism... but let me point out one obvious fact about nationalism:<br>
nationalism is not made to lessn the culture gap, it is designed _explicitly_ to divide people.  if you disagree with this aspect of nationalism... well, you don't believe in the legitamacy of the nation-state... hm... my thoughts are jumping everywhere... but anyways, yea, what all of you are talking about is not merely a language issue, it's about the basic concept of nationalism. <p><center><A HREF="http://www.clanautumnwood.com" TARGET="_top">
<img src="http://www.clanautumnwood.com/tanikaze/tanisig.jpg"
